title: Rush Limbaugh - A Concentrated Pile Of Human Waste
description: Folks, Rush Limbaugh likes to tell us he is the "great truth detector." Rush also claims to be an example of patriotism who exhibits a high degree of moral behavior. Rush Limbaugh has nothing to do with truth and morals, nor is he an example of patriotic behavior.  Rush Limbaugh evaded serving his country at a time when it needed him. By getting his private doctor to state he had a pilonidal cyst on his bottom and needed a 4f (unfit for military service), Rush avoided the Vietnam war. Allegedly, he had either an "anal cyst" or a "ingrown hair follicle".  Just imagine the dripping scorn and merciless sarcasm Rush would unleash, with the revelation that a prominent Democrat had skipped out of a war, over something like that.  Friends, Rush Limbaugh is a highly paid propagandist and self-serving demagogue, in the service of a radical right-wing sect. Limbaugh regularly feeds his audience a diet of lies, disinformation, misstatements and distortions. He is part of a cabal of pundits, commentators, and "reporters"-call it the Limbaugh-Hannity-Drudge axis. This fifth column in the forth estate is made up of propagandists pretending to be journalists. Through multiple overlapping outlets covering radio, television, and the Internet, they relentlessly force-feed the American people right-wing talking points and ultraconservative dogma disguised as news and infotainment-24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year.  Even with the hot air and relentless rhetoric from  propagandists such as Rush Limbaugh, events have landed President George W. Bush firmly out of favor with mainstream America. Still, Rush infers (of course) that everybody who doesn't approve of Bush's performance and policies, is some sort of unpatriotic-America-hating traitor.  Clearly, Rush Limbaugh/Bush-Cheney, are disingenuous and dangerous extremists, with an agenda that conflicts with mainstream America. title: You I Love Theatrical - www.PictureThisEntertainment.com
description:
Vera and Tim are successful young professionals living fast-paced lives in ultra-modern Moscow. She's a beautiful, famous newscaster. He's a creative idea-guy in an advertising firm. ("Freedom is cola!") Their lives crackle with the capitalist energy of excess, anxiety, consumption, and stress— and they are in love.
 
 Everything changes one night when Tim accidentally drives his car into Uloomji, a young Kalmyk day worker. (The Kalmyks are a semi-nomadic people of Mongolian decent.) The two men are immediately drawn to each other, and begin a torrid affair that involves howling and knocking over a lot of furniture. Tim is attracted to Uloomji's exotic demeanor, and liberated by his impulsiveness and lack of inhibition. To Uloomji, Tim embodies a kind of class and refinement he sees only in magazines.
 
 Vera struggles to comprehend their bond and her boyfriend's erratic behavior, and is dragged reluctantly into a bizarre love triangle. Before long, all three lives unravel, exemplified by a visit to a Buddhist healer, a three-way in the bathroom of a gay bar, a faked death, and a kidnapping.
 
 YOU I LOVE is reminiscent of the work of Pedro Almodovar, particularly in the way it relishes saturated symbolism, obsessive love, and zany, character-driven melodrama.

La historia de esa noche de jacuzzi empezó con unos masajes, siguió con los jueguecitos del agua y el limón y terminó con la tórrida escena del jacuzzi ante la atenta mirada del resto de compañeros dentro de la casa. title: The difficult birth of tomorrow
description:
This short film is a blend of images captured in lives of people of different religions, beliefs.
 
 Theory behind the film
 
 Most of the religions of the ancient civilizations have vanished from our lives or ended up in history books. They lost their followers. They died, because they got old and out of date, obsolete.
 New religions were born, exciting ones, promising ones, even outrageous. They were useful to the people, so they accepted them as thier ways of life, as they once accepted the eye for an eye law as it was better than the vendicitve laws they had before, like killing out a whole family for one little scar. Of course newever laws emerged in advanced civilizations, like were the Romans. Law of today is still based on the ancient roman law. Religions are not earthly law, they are teachings about life in general and spcifically about how communities should live.
 Today these once new religions are growing old and are becoming obsolete. People are more and more finding it hard to try and blend the old ways with their new chalanges of today.
 History will repeat itself and these religions will end up in history books.
 Many new religions arose, trying to take the places of the old religions. Most have failed, for instance, communism, with it's idealism, which does not allow supreme beings, as are gods and goddesses, but it does worship idealistic figures almost like gods, Karl Marx, Lenin, Stalin, Mao, etc.
 Many others have won the hearts of the followers, but have not quite won over the old religions. Science and atheism are most prosperous, but do not answer all things in life, as many scientists hold beliefs, like the christian fact that the Earth was created about 6000 years ago, and at the same time do researches related to scientific facts about creation of Earth and universe. Why?
 I predict that the one knowledge to overthrow old religions is yet to come and it is not science, science might give life to it, but science will look old compared to it. Followers of science and it's monks, the scientists and researchres, might even oppose this new teaching.
 Will it be classified as a religion? Science is trying very hard to not be labeled as a religion, it claims to be objective and that it's teachings, the many theories, are based on facts. The old religions claimed also they were the only real truth, as the teachings were words of the creator. The reality is, that science cannot prove or disprove all things we experience in life, even the most basic sciences are based on axioms, self-evident or universally recognized truths, self-evident principles or those that are accepted as true without proof as the basis for argument. Science is suppose to have all her theories proven, yet the basis for her argumets is accepted without neccessary proof.
 Furthermore, science has many streams, that are not growing friendships amongst them, as do the old religions. You have to believe and trust, have faith, to completely embracem science as the answer to life.
 The one teaching of life of tomorrow will be the key to unlocking the secrets of life. Like the DNA is the code for living beings, so will this teaching teach of the code of existance, like the DNA code evolves with evolution, so will this teaching evolve through human time.
 
 This film is useful for comparing various feelings one gets observing these images that carry different messages about different religions, beliefs.
 
 Enjoy! Do not get hostile against others!

 Bigger Than Jesus: The Diary of a Rock and Roll Fan is the popular one-man stage show that celebrates rock and roll and its power to transform a young man's life. title: Bay Area Backstage - Phil Anselmo Interview
description: Executive Producer Michael Magic Kerman interviews Phil Anselmo on the tour Bus During the Superjoint Ritual Tour. This is the Press from the Then Music writer for the Metro. Ramble On Superjoint Ritual's Phil Anselmo went on revolutionary tirades last Wednesday at the Edge   By Sarah Quelland  WE LOVE YOU. Spread the word. Hail Satan." Hail Satan? Yep. That's how Phil Anselmo ended the Superjoint Ritual concert last Wednesday (Dec. 17) at the Edge in Palo Alto. After reminding his fans--a rough lot of bikers, metal heads and musicians--that his was "the most terrifying band," he mysteriously crooned some Led Zeppelin ("and she's buying a stairway to heaven") before leaving the stage.  Superjoint Ritual is the former Pantera frontman's current active project, and this one features Hank Williams III on bass, Kevin Bond and Jimmy Bower on guitars and Joe Fazzio on drums. The band hit the Edge with DevilDriver (former Coal Chamber frontman Dez Fafara's new band) for a night of concentrated anger and hate.  There's absolutely nothing modern or mainstream about Superjoint Ritual. Anselmo described his band's songs as "short blasts of hardcore blood" and said, to those who weren't around to witness Agnostic Front and early Slayer, "We're givin' you a fuckin' beautiful example of what it was like."  Superjoint's songs are violent and threatening, with titles like "Stealing a Page or Two From Armed and Radical Pagans." But what's really fascinating is Anselmo's well-known tendency to launch into bizarre diatribes between songs. On Wednesday night, he did not disappoint. At the moment, Anselmo seems to be existing in some paranoid parallel universe filled with enemies, and touring seems to be his way of achieving a platform to spout off his radical religious and political views in front of a receptive audience.  As a bandleader, Anselmo is a demigod. When he asks for a counterclockwise circle pit, he gets one instantly. When he wants to see hands up way in the back, arms rise immediately. When he bellows, "Let me hear some goddamn noise!" fans answer with steamroller screams. Few frontmen have the credibility and authority to command such respect.  After ranting about Saddam Hussein ("Saddam Hussein, we got you motherfucker. I am truly proud") and railing against "Bible thumpers" who he says are foolishly reading that religious text instead of learning how to defend themselves with nuclear weapons, Anselmo informed the crowd, "Once America turns, it's up to the free thinkers and the heathens and the pagans, man. Because when the time comes, I'm gonna rally. We're gonna be a dangerous force, and we're gonna have to be reckoned with."  It sounds like he's building himself an army and preparing to lead a revolution. To him, the stage is a pulpit, the fans are his congregation and he's preaching the absolute power of metal. He also seems to be in a serious measuring contest with his former Pantera band mates and anyone else who dares to challenge his honor. He proclaimed himself "the king of heavy metal hardcore music" and insisted, "We are the heaviest fuckin' band."  Superjoint played songs off its two albums, Use Once and Destroy ("The Alcoholik," "Fuck Your Enemy," "Ozena") and A Lethal Dose of American Hatred ("Personal Insult," "Dress Like a Target," "The Destruction of a Person," "Waiting for the Turning Point," "Permanently"). But between songs, Anselmo repeatedly returned to the concept of war, as if it's been a constant weight on his mind. He talked of enemies and of being prepared and sounded like a man with a bomb shelter stockpiled with rations, weapons and ammunition. "Believe me, there are targets, man," he told the crowd at one point, and he said cryptically that when Superjoint returns to the area, "I promise you by then a lot of things will be clear." Anselmo's message is anything but clear, but it does make his band all the more terrifying.  Those reading this on Wednesday can tune into R 2 Cents to catch an interview with Anselmo plus live footage from the concert. Bay Area Backstage 1030pm Ch 15 Wed 12 am Fri Ch 30 www.bayareabackstage.com

title: (6) Napoleon Dynamite: Nepteam Forever!
description: [Rated: PG]  A science project that doubled as a fan film (or vice versa), "Nepteam" was the second video I made with my sister. The assignment was to create a video about the planet Neptune. As usual, we had some fun with it.  NOTES:  - "BSF" is short for "BSFilms/Ben Sweeney Films." - I wrote most of the script, which was probably a mistake. - Kip's "queso" was melted american cheese with food coloring... It tasted okay. - After a day of deliberation from the managers, we were not allowed to film in the Goodwill store. A scene was planned in which Napoleon would discover the teleportation device. - I kinda doubt that anyone in my sister's class got the "Star Trek / A-Team" references (except maybe her teacher). - The "teleportation device" is actually an old editing machine. - After I forced many takes of the countdown on  "Napoleon" (SEE- Bloopers), I decided to use only one shot. - My "blue screen" was an emergency blanket. The special effect would've benefited from removing the creases. - People claim that leaving the group stranded on the planet is sad. I don't know why I wrote it that way, but at least there's the final scene.  FUN FACTS:  - I retired my glitchy camcorder in the middle of shooting. I bought a new one with the sole intention of finishing the project... (Yeah, that's the ticket). - "Kip" apparently stripped the gears of the blender. - A unicorn is displayed on the monitor as Kip first enters the computer room. - I forgot that Kevin ("Uncle Rico") put the milk back in the fridge... My mom used it the next day.
